TY  - JOUR
AB  - Faced with numerous potential catastrophes&#x2014;nuclear and bioterrorism, mega-viruses, climate change, and others&#x2014;which should society attempt to avert? A policy to avert one catastrophe considered in isolation might be evaluated in cost-benefit terms. But because society faces multiple catastrophes, simple cost-benefit analysis fails: even if the benefit of averting each one exceeds the cost, we should not necessarily avert them all. We explore the policy interdependence of catastrophic events, and develop a rule for determining which catastrophes should be averted and which should not.
